This article is a proclamation by President Barack Obama declaring February 2009 as National African American History Month. The proclamation highlights the unique and rich history of African Americans in the United States and their contributions to American society. It emphasizes the struggle for recognition and equality faced by African Americans throughout history, as well as their role in shaping American culture, science, literature, and architecture. The theme for that year's observance is "The Quest for Black Citizenship in the Americas," focusing on the evolution of the country and how African Americans have played a significant role in advancing the ideals of a more perfect union. The proclamation also acknowledges the 100th anniversary of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) and calls upon public officials, educators, librarians, and all Americans to observe the month with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs that raise awareness and appreciation of African American history.